(Amund O. Ringsrud was born to Ole and Karen Ringsurd in Norway in 1854. At a young age, Amund and his family immigrated to America, settling in Elk Point, SD. Much time would pass before the young Ringsrud would become a successful businessman and politician. With no formal education beyond grade school, Ringsrud got his start in merchandising at the age of 31. In 1883, Governor Ordway, appointed Amund Ringsrud as a member of the Regents of the Agricultural College in Brookings. This Board was responsible for the initial establishment and operation of the college. He was on the committee for Farm & Buildings, and the committee on College Lands. Elected as delegate to the Constitutional Convention of 1889, Ringsrud served on the Committee on Congressional and Legislative Apportionment, The Revenue and Finance committee, the Roads - Bridges and other Internal Improvements Committee and was Chairman of the Public Accounts and Expenditures committee. Elected as the first Secretary of State of South Dakota in 1889, Mr. Ringsrud served two terms.... Died January 8, 1931, in Elk Point, South Dakota)
